extends /views/templates/layouts/_base

append variables
	- pagetitle = "PanelControl — Getting started"

block content
	.lane
		.container
			.page-header
				h1 PanelControl
				p.lead An external controller for a PanelSet. It wires the triggers; PanelSet switches the panels.

	+section("What it does")
		p A #[strong PanelSet] switches panels, but it does not bind the clicks on your tabs — that has always been a little glue you write by hand. #[strong PanelControl] is that glue, as a class: drop it on the element that holds your triggers and it activates the right panel on click, adds keyboard navigation, and reflects state back onto the controls.
		p It finds its PanelSet through the panels the triggers point at, so the control can live #[strong anywhere] in the DOM — it does not need to sit next to the PanelSet. One PanelControl drives one PanelSet.

	+section("Installation")
		p PanelControl ships inside the #[code panelset] package — nothing extra to install. Import it next to PanelSet, or load the one script.

		+codeblock('JS').
			import { PanelSet, PanelControl } from 'panelset';
			import 'panelset/style.css';

		+codeblock('HTML')
			link(rel="stylesheet" href="panelset.css")
			script(src="panelset.js")

		p With the script tag, #[code window.PanelControl] is available and #[code register()] has already defined #[code &lt;ps-panelcontrol&gt;]. See the #[a(href="/panelcontrol/integrations/webcomponent.html") Web Component] page for that path.

	+section("Markup")
		p Put #[code data-panelcontrol] on the element holding your triggers. Each trigger points at a panel with #[code aria-controls]. Add #[code role="tablist"] (with #[code role="tab"] on the buttons) to switch on keyboard navigation.

		.card
			.demo
				nav.tabs(role="tablist" data-panelcontrol)
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="gs-1" aria-selected="true") Features
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="gs-2") Pricing
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="gs-3") Support
				#gs(data-panelset)
					.panel-wrapper
						#gs-1.active(role="tabpanel" aria-label="Features")
							h3 Features
							p Click a tab, or focus the strip and use the arrow keys.
						#gs-2(role="tabpanel" hidden aria-label="Pricing")
							h3 Pricing
							p One plan, no surprises.
						#gs-3(role="tabpanel" hidden aria-label="Support")
							h3 Support
							p Friendly help when you need it.

			+codeblock('HTML')
				nav.tabs(role="tablist" data-panelcontrol)
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="gs-1" aria-selected="true") Features
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="gs-2") Pricing
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="gs-3") Support
				+n
				#gs(data-panelset)
					.panel-wrapper
						#gs-1.active(role="tabpanel") …
						#gs-2(role="tabpanel" hidden) …
						#gs-3(role="tabpanel" hidden) …

	+section("Initializing")
		p Initialise PanelSet and PanelControl. Order does not matter — PanelControl resolves its PanelSet lazily.

		+codeblock('JS').
			import { PanelSet, PanelControl } from 'panelset';

			PanelSet.init();
			PanelControl.init();            // every [data-panelcontrol]
			PanelControl.init('#my-tabs');  // or a specific control

	+section("Layout patterns")
		p The control's #[code role] decides its keyboard model — and how much ARIA you take on.
		dl
			dt: strong Horizontal tablist
			dd #[code role="tablist"] with #[code role="tab"] children. Left / Right arrows, #[code Home] / #[code End], roving tabindex. The default, best-supported pattern.
			dt: strong Vertical tablist
			dd The same, plus #[code aria-orientation="vertical"] — arrows become Up / Down; everything else is identical. CSS lays it out as a sidebar. Covers most "sidebar that switches panels" needs, with no extra ARIA.
			dt: strong Tree (planned)
			dd #[code role="tree"] is a different interaction model — collapsible nodes, #[code aria-expanded], Right / Left to expand and collapse. Genuinely more complex, and only needed for #[em hierarchical] navigation (grouped or collapsible steps). It will arrive later behind a #[code mode: 'tree'] option, most likely driven by PanelFlow. For a flat sidebar, reach for a vertical tablist.

		p See #[a(href="/panelcontrol/examples.html") Examples] for vertical tablists, the activation modes, and closable megamenus.

	+section("Scope")
		p PanelControl wires controls and reflects state — activation, keyboard nav, roving #[code tabindex], #[code aria-selected] / disabled. It also exposes #[code setTabState(id, 'disabled' | 'enabled')] so external code can lock or unlock a tab; PanelControl just applies it.
		p Validation, Previous / Next flow, step gating, and persistence are #[strong not] part of PanelControl — those belong to a separate flow controller (PanelFlow, planned) that calls #[code setTabState] when a step should lock. Strictly one-way: #[code PanelFlow → PanelControl → PanelSet].
		p Next: every option in #[a(href="/panelcontrol/configuration.html") Configuration], and the method list in the #[a(href="/panelcontrol/api.html") API] reference.


append styles
	style.
		#gs {
			border: 1px solid var(--border-default);
			border-radius: 8px;
		}
		#gs .panel-wrapper [role="tabpanel"] {
			padding: 1.25rem;
		}


append scripts
	if isProd
		script(src=`${basePath}lib/panelset.js` vite-ignore)
		script.
			PanelSet.init();
			PanelControl.init();
	else
		script(type="module").
			import { PanelSet, PanelControl } from 'panelset';
			PanelSet.init({ debug: true });
			PanelControl.init({ debug: true });
